The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Raipur, April 12 (PTI): Four persons, including two security personnel, were killed in a landmine explosion by Maoists while six rebels were gunned down during two encounters in the Bastar region of Chhattisgarh today.           
	The blast occurred near National Highway 16 where a joint patrolling team of the CRPF and local police was on clearance duty for the Lok Sabha polls, superintendent of police of Bijapur district Ankit Garg said.                   
	 Bhubaneswar/New Delhi (PTI): The Election Commission has decided to slap two more charges on the BJP candidate from Kandhamal, Ashok Sahu, for his alleged hate speech. The charges relate to statements conducive to public mischief and injuring or defiling place of worship to insult a religion. Sahu may seek anticipatory bail on Monday.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): The railways will run more than 4,500 trains this summer, anticipating a heavy rush during the season. The ministry has received permission from the Election Commission. As many as 90 pairs of summer specials will be operated between April and June in 13 of the 16 zones, an official said.                   
	 Dehra Dun (PTI): The Centre plans to increase the area of the Corbett Tiger Reserve in Kumaon amid concern over the dwindling tiger population. Under the new plan, the reserve will include the Jim Corbett National Park and Sonanadi wildlife sanctuary.                   
	 Mumbai (PTI): Ajmal Kasab will appear in person for the first time in the Mumbai attacks case on April 15 before a special court at the Arthur Road jail. Earlier, he had been produced through video-conferencing.                   
	 Srinagar (PTI): A rare granite sculpture of goddess Lakshmi, believed to be 1,400 years old, has been found at a village along the Jhelum in Anantnag district of Jammu and Kashmir. The sculpture was found by farmers.                                                                                                                           
